<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 35 companion (Teeth and Speed — branch protection, merge queues, trunk-based development,
    and pre-commit hooks with local/CI parity). This is the CONFIG-centric peer shape of Chapter 33
    (75) and Chapter 27 (27): the artifacts a team adopts are configuration, and the runnable,
    unit-tested part is the one load-bearing decision the chapter argues for.

    The configuration the chapter teaches lives beside the build, NOT run by it:
      - config/branch-protection/ruleset.yml — a branch-protection ruleset (required status checks,
        required review, linear history, restricted force-push/deletion) that gives the gate TEETH.
      - .pre-commit-config.yaml — fast hooks at commit time (format-check, a fast Checkstyle subset,
        a secrets scan) that give the gate SPEED at the keyboard.
    Both name hosted/SaaS surfaces (GitHub rulesets, the pre-commit framework + its hook repos), which
    SOURCE-PIN.md §5 records as rolling/SaaS — so their identifiers are DATED-AT-USE (2026-06), not
    timeless, and are flagged for pinning at adoption (09-flags/).

    What is runnable and machine-checked here is the chapter's central claim made executable:
    local <-> CI PARITY, in org.acme.parity.GateParity — the assertion that the gate set a developer
    runs locally (the pre-commit hooks) is consistent with the gate set CI enforces (the required
    status checks). That makes "green locally" predict "green in CI" a property a test pins, not a hope.
    The honest backstop is in the code's comments and its failure path: hooks are FEEDBACK (bypassable,
    install-dependent), CI + branch protection are the ENFORCEMENT.

    JDK-only at runtime (the parity logic is plain Java); the only added GAVs are the test libraries,
    whose versions are inherited from the companion-code aggregator. The module is held to its own
    `quality` gate (Checkstyle + SpotBugs) so it dogfoods the book and the same local check it ships.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <relativePath>../pom.xml</relativePath>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>branch-protection-precommit-parity</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 35 — Teeth and Speed (branch-protection-precommit-parity)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      JDK-only at runtime: the parity check is plain Java, and the surfaces the chapter names (the
      git platform's branch protection, the pre-commit framework) run outside this build, not as
      runtime dependencies here. The test libraries are the only additions, and their versions come
      from the companion-code aggregator's dependencyManagement — no version literal lives here.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    The static-analysis gate (Chapter 16), opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays fast. This
    profile IS one half of the parity the chapter teaches: it runs the SAME Checkstyle the
    .pre-commit-config.yaml runs at the keyboard, so the local hook and the build agree. The
    maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled engine; it is overridden to the pinned engine via a
    plugin-level dependency (the build plugin and the analyzer engine are separate versions). The module
    is a direct child of the companion-code root, which pins no quality profile of its own, so the
    profile is declared here (the same shape the peer modules use) and reads the config under this
    module's own config/ dir — keeping the module self-contained.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <!--
            SpotBugs: the bytecode vantage point (Chapter 16), complementary to Checkstyle's source
            view. This module's model types are immutable records and an unmodifiable set, and the
            parity check exposes no mutable state, so the representation-exposure detectors stay quiet
            without suppression. The exclude filter is kept (empty) so a future, genuinely-reviewed
            suppression has a home with a reason, rather than being added inline.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
